  <static seed="79" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions90.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{ 3 + \frac{5}{7}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{26}{7}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>When doing arithmetic with fractions, it is helpful to rewrite any integers as fractions:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 3 = \frac{3}{1} }</m></p>
<p>Next, to add two fractions, we need to find a common denominator. In this case, it is simply the second denominator <m>7</m>. We will rewrite the first fraction:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{3}{1} \amp = \frac{3 \cdot 7}{1 \cdot 7}\\ \amp = \frac{21}{7} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Finally, we add the numerators and keep the denominator unchanged. The whole process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   3 + \frac{5}{7}
        \amp = \frac{21}{7} + \frac{5}{7} \\
        \amp = \frac{21 + 5}{7} \\
        \amp = \frac{26}{7}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer to this question is  <m>{{\frac{26}{7}}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
